stianization of the world. Hammond presents a capacious portrait of the relationship between the evangelical business community and the New Deal—and in doing so makes important contributions to American religious history, business history, and the history of the American state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aBusinessxReligious aspectsxProtestant churches. 0aBusiness--Religious aspects--Protestant churches. 0aCapitalismxReligious aspectsxProtestant churches. 0aChristianityzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aEvangelicalismxEconomic aspectszUnited States. 0aEvangelicalismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aConservatism.  aEntrepreneurialism.  aEvangelicalism.  aFundamentalism.  aNew Deal.  aPolitics.  aReligion.1 aDochuk, Darren, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831107119360 cprintz978022650977840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226509808423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226509808/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles